Anonymous Tue 24 Sep 2019 02:40:53 No.25605319 Report
Quoted By: >>25605356 >>25605598
>>25605171

First person - any length, but you want to have a degree of unreliability in the narration and need to restrict the pov
Second person - short stories, but where you've loaded the situation so the character is a framework but unique to each reader. Also unreliable because the reader will be guessing at what the character is failing to notice
Third person - you need freedom outside the constraints of the previous two

The best perspective is the one that works for the theme(s) of the piece

  • Report

second tends to be the best for action-oriented narratives as well, since it physically puts the reader in the protag's shoes
first and third both concern other people, so they're slightly less in-the-moment

However, one of the biggest flaws I've found in writing in second person is the narration itself. Done wrong, there's so much passive voice that no matter how much action there is the character is flat. That's why the piece I'm writing now has taken so long. It was OK in second, but once I realized a few facts about the main character and handed my first reader a revision of the first two chapters in first person we agreed that it went from good to great
Of course, there's also the emotional impact of the story. Tell it in the wrong perspective and the scene will punch differently.
I should work more on shorter pieces and polish my skills across all perspectives, but I'm dying to get the editing done on 100K+ words and start dropping chapters
